` is measurable with respect to the σ-algebra generated by `Z` and `Y`, and `t` is measurable with respect to the σ-algebra generated by `Z`, we have `μ(X⁻¹(s) ∩ t) = μ(X⁻¹(s)) * μ(t)`.\n\nIn our case, we need to show that for any sets `s`, `t` such that `s` is measurable with respect to the σ-algebra generated by `Z` and `fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)`, and `t` is measurable with respect to the σ-algebra generated by `Z`, we have `μ(X⁻¹(s) ∩ t) = μ(X⁻¹(s)) * μ(t)`.\n\nThe key insight is that `fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)` is essentially `Y × Z`. The σ-algebra generated by `Z` and `Y × Z` is the same as the σ-algebra generated by `Z` and `Y`. This is because `Y × Z` contains all the information from `Y` and `Z`. Given `Z`, `Y` is redundant.\n\nSo we can use the original conditional independence hypothesis `h` to prove the goal.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Measure.ProbabilityMeasure\nimport Mathlib.Probability.Independence.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Probability.Independence.Conditional\n\nopen MeasureTheory ProbabilityTheory Finset\nopen scoped ENNReal NNReal\n```\n\nNow we define the lemma statement.\n\n```tactics\nlemma condIndepFun",
      "\n  have h1 : X ⟂ᵢ[Z, hZ; μ] (fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)) := by\n```\n\nTo show this, we need to use the definition of conditional independence and the hypothesis `h`.\n\n```tactics\n    rw [cond_indep_iff] at h ⊢\n```\n\nNow we need to show that for any measurable sets `s` and `t`, the measure of the intersection is the product of the measures.\n\n```tactics\n    intro s hs t ht\n```\n\nNow, we need to compute `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ ((fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)) ⁻¹' t))`.\nThis set is `{ω | X ω ∈ s ∧ (Y ω, Z ω) ∈ t}`.\nLet `t₁ = π₁ t` and `t₂ = π₂ t`. Then `(fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)) ⁻¹' t = Y⁻¹' t₁ ∩ Z⁻¹' t₂`.\nSo, we need `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' t₁ ∩ Z⁻¹' t₂))`.\n\nFrom the hypothesis `h`, we have `X` and `Y` are conditionally independent given `Z`.\nSo, `h` gives us `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Z⁻¹' t₂)) = μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Z⁻¹' t₂) / μ (Z⁻¹' t₂)`.\nWe need to compute `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' t₁ ∩ Z⁻¹' t₂))`.\nThis is `μ ((X ⁻¹' s ∩ Z⁻¹' t₂) ∩ Y⁻¹' t₁)`.\nUsing the property of measures and the hypothesis `h`, we can derive this as `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' t₁)`.\nWe need this to equal `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ ((fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)) ⁻¹' t) / μ ((fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)) ⁻¹' t)`.\nThe denominator is `μ (Y⁻¹' t₁ ∩ Z⁻¹' t₂)`.\nFrom `h`, we can compute this as `μ (Y⁻¹' t₁)`.\nSo we need `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' t₁) = μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' t₁ ∩ Z⁻¹' t₂) / μ (Y⁻¹' t₁ ∩ Z⁻¹' t₂)`.\nThis simplifies to an identity, so the equality holds.\n\nLet's complete the proof.\n\n```tactics\n    have h2 : ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ ((fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)) ⁻¹' t)) = (X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) := by\n      ext ω\n      simp [Set.mem_inter_iff, Set.mem_preimage, Prod.mk.injEq]\n```\n\nNow, we can rewrite the measure using this equality.\n\n```tactics\n    rw [h2]\n```\n\nNow, we need to compute `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)))`.\nThis is `μ ((X ⁻¹' s ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) ∩ Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`.\nLet's compute this using the hypothesis `h`.\n\nFrom `h`, we have `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))) = μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) / μ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))`.\nTo compute `μ ((X ⁻¹' s ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) ∩ Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`, we can use the property of conditional independence.\nThis is `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t)) ∩ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)))`.\nFrom `h`, this is `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))) * μ ((Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))) / μ ((Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)))`.\nBut `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t)))` is `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t)))`.\nFrom `h`, this is `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t)) / μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`.\nSo putting it all together, we get:\n`μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t)) ∩ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))) = (μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t)) / μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))) * μ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) / μ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))`.\nThis simplifies to `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`.\nBut we need `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))) = μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ ((fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)) ⁻¹' t) / μ ((fun ω ↦ (Y ω, Z ω)) ⁻¹' t)`.\nThe right side is `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) / μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))`.\nBut `μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) = μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`.\nSo the right side is `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`.\nThis is equal to the left side, which is `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`.\n\nLet's complete the proof using Lean.\n\n```tactics\n    have h3 : μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))) = μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t)) := by\n```\n\nTo prove this, we need to use the hypothesis `h` which states `X` and `Y` are conditionally independent given `Z`.\n\n```tactics\n      have h4 : μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))) = μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) / μ (Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) := by\n        apply h\n```\n\nNow, we need to compute `μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)))`.\nThis is `μ ((X ⁻¹' s ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) ∩ Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`.\nUsing the property of measures and the hypothesis `h`, we can derive this as `μ (X ⁻¹' s) * μ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))`.\n\n```tactics\n      have h5 : μ ((X ⁻¹' s) ∩ (Y⁻¹' (π₁ t) ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t))) = μ ((X ⁻¹' s ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) ∩ Y⁻¹' (π₁ t)) := by\n        congr\n        ext ω\n        simp [Set.mem_inter_iff]\n```\n\nNow, we can compute `μ ((X ⁻¹' s ∩ Z⁻¹' (π₂ t)) ∩ Y⁻¹' (π₁ t))` using the hypothesis `h`.\n\n```tacti